Let A and B be two sets with n elements in common.
Then, A × B contains n elements common to B × A.
Let A = {a1, a2, a3, .... an} and B = {b1, b2, b3, .... bn}
Then, A × B = {(a1, b1), (a1, b2), .... (a1, bn), (a2, b1), (a2, b2), .... (a2, bn), ............. , (an, b1), (an, b2), .... (an, bn)}
Therefore, the total number of elements in A × B = n^2
Similarly, B × A = {(b1, a1), (b1, a2), .... (b1, an), (b2, a1), (b2, a2), .... (b2, an), ............. , (bn, a1), (bn, a2), .... (bn, an)}
Therefore, the total number of elements in B × A = n^2
Hence, the two sets have n^2 elements in common.

